"title": "5098: John the Baptist",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5098",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>The forerunner of Jesus Christ, born to elderly parents of the Aaronic line. His public ministry began in the Judean wilderness with a call to repentance and baptism. His ministry is seen as a fulfilment of OT prophecy, in preparation for the ministry of Jesus Christ. He was executed by Herod.</p>\n<h2>John's birth and early years</h2>\n<h3>His birth and naming</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:57-Luke1:60\">LUK 1:57–1:60</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:5-Luke1:13\">LUK 1:5–1:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:61-Luke1:66\">LUK 1:61–1:66</a></p>\n<h3>Prophetic words over his life</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:14-Luke1:17\">LUK 1:14–1:17</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:76-Luke1:79\">LUK 1:76–1:79</a></p>\n<h3>He was related to Jesus Christ</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:36\">LUK 1:36</a></p>\n<h3>His early years</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:80\">LUK 1:80</a></p>\n<h2>John's ministry</h2>\n<h3>His simple lifestyle</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:4\">MAT 3:4</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:6\">MRK 1:6</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt11:18\">MAT 11:18</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke7:33\">LUK 7:33</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke7:24-Luke7:25\">LUK 7:24–7:25</a></p>\n<h3>His call for repentance</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:3\">LUK 3:3</a></strong> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:1\">MAT 3:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:4\">MRK 1:4</a></p>\n<h3>He fulfilled Isaiah's prophecy</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:3\">MAT 3:3</a></strong> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:2-Mark1:3\">MRK 1:2–1:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:4-Luke3:6\">LUK 3:4–3:6</a> <em>Just as roads were improved in the ancient world in preparation for the visit of a king, so John calls for people to prepare spiritually and morally for the imminent coming of the Messiah.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa40:3\">ISA 40:3</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:23\">JHN 1:23</a></p>\n<h3>His practice of baptism</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:4-Mark1:5\">MRK 1:4–1:5</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:5-Matt3:6\">MAT 3:5–3:6</a> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John3:23\">JHN 3:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John10:40\">JHN 10:40</a></p>\n<h3>His challenge to established religion</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:7-Matt3:10\">MAT 3:7–3:10</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:7-Luke3:9\">LUK 3:7–3:9</a> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:10-Luke3:14\">LUK 3:10–3:14</a></p>\n<h3>The contrast of his own baptism with that which the Messiah would bring</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:15-Luke3:17\">LUK 3:15–3:17</a></strong> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:11-Matt3:12\">MAT 3:11–3:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:7-Mark1:8\">MRK 1:7–1:8</a></p>\n<h3>His testimony to Jesus Christ</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:15\">JHN 1:15</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:6-John1:8\">JHN 1:6–1:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:21-John1:27\">JHN 1:21–1:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John10:41\">JHN 10:41</a></p>\n<h3>He recognises that his own ministry must decrease, while that of Jesus Christ will increase</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John3:27-John3:30\">JHN 3:27–3:30</a></strong></p>\n<h2>John's baptising of Jesus Christ</h2>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:13-Matt3:15\">MAT 3:13–3:15</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:9\">MRK 1:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:21\">LUK 3:21</a> <em>John's reluctance to baptise Jesus Christ lay in his recognition of who Jesus was and the apparent inappropriateness of such a baptism</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:29-John1:34\">JHN 1:29–1:34</a></p>\n<h2>John and his disciples</h2>\n<h3>John had disciples</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John1:35-John1:37\">JHN 1:35–1:37</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John3:25\">JHN 3:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John4:1\">JHN 4:1</a></p>\n<h3>He taught them to pray</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke11:1\">LUK 11:1</a></p>\n<h3>His disciples become envious of Jesus Christ</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John3:25-John3:26\">JHN 3:25–3:26</a></p>\n<h3>He sends his disciples to question Jesus Christ</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt11:2-Matt11:6\">MAT 11:2–11:6</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke7:18-Luke7:23\">LUK 7:18–7:23</a> <em>Locked up in prison, John needed reassurance that his expectations about Jesus Christ had been well-founded.</em></p>\n<h3>John's disciples and the first Christians</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:24-Acts19:7\">ACT 18:24–19:7</a></p>\n<h2>John's imprisonment and death</h2>\n<h3>His confrontation with Herod leads to his imprisonment</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke3:19-Luke3:20\">LUK 3:19–3:20</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt14:3-Matt14:5\">MAT 14:3–14:5</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark6:17-Mark6:20\">MRK 6:17–6:20</a></p>\n<h3>His execution</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt14:6-Matt14:12\">MAT 14:6–14:12</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark6:21-Mark6:29\">MRK 6:21–6:29</a></p>\n<h2>Some thought Jesus Christ to be John risen from the dead</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark8:27-Mark8:28\">MRK 8:27–8:28</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt16:13-Matt16:14\">MAT 16:13–16:14</a> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt14:1-Matt14:2\">MAT 14:1–14:2</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark6:14-Mark6:16\">MRK 6:14–6:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke9:7-Luke9:9\">LUK 9:7–9:9</a></p>\n<h2>Jesus Christ's estimation of John</h2>\n<h3>Jesus Christ honours him</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt11:11\">MAT 11:11</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke7:28\">LUK 7:28</a></p>\n<h3>Jesus Christ sees him as marking the end of the old covenant and the arrival of the kingdom</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke16:16\">LUK 16:16</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt11:12-Matt11:13\">MAT 11:12–11:13</a></p>\n<h3>Jesus Christ sees him as the promised Elijah</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt11:14\">MAT 11:14</a></strong> <em>On the basis of Malachi's prophecy (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mal4:5\">Mal 4:5</a>), it was widely accepted that Elijah must come before the Messiah could appear. This identification would have been reinforced by John dressing like Elijah (see <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs1:8\">2Ki 1:8</a>).</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt11:10\">MAT 11:10</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mal3:1\">MAL 3:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt17:11-Matt17:13\">MAT 17:11–17:13</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark9:11-Mark9:13\">MRK 9:11–9:13</a></p>",
